 # ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE
 
 Summaries for scanner-reported CVEs that Debian or upstream treat as non-actionable for stock OS packages in this image.
 
 ## CVE-2018-20796
 
 ## Overview: What Is CVE-2018-20796?
 
 CVE-2018-20796 is reported against GNU C Library (`glibc`) and concerns **uncontrolled recursion** in POSIX regular-expression matching (`regexec` / related code paths such as `check_dst_limits_calc_pos_1` in `posix/regexec.c`). Crafted patterns can drive deep recursion and **resource exhaustion** (denial of service via stack or CPU), not memory corruption in the usual exploit sense.
 
 **Glibc’s security policy explicitly excludes this class of issue from treatment as a security vulnerability**, and Debian’s tracker marks it **unimportant** with **no fixed version** aimed at “closing” the CVE.
 
 ---
 
 ## Debian tracker: “Not treated as vulnerability”
 
 On the [Debian security tracker](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2018-20796), **Notes** reference upstream discussion and state (in substance) that the issue is **not treated as a vulnerability**, with a link to **[glibc Security Exceptions](https://sourceware.org/glibc/wiki/Security%20Exceptions)**.
 
 Release rows may still show **vulnerable** for `glibc` while the **fixed version** column for unstable shows **(unfixed)** and urgency **unimportant** — meaning **no CVE-driven security update** is planned in the same way as for typical glibc flaws.
 
 ---
 
 ## Why Scanners Still Flag Trixie and Other Debian Releases
 
 Security scanners match:
 
 - Installed `glibc` source package and version
 - CVE metadata (e.g. CWE-674, availability impact)
 
 They often **do not** encode glibc’s **security exceptions** or Debian’s **unimportant** classification, so dashboards show a **HIGH**-style CVE even when **distributors and upstream reject it as a security boundary**.
 
 ---
 
 ## CVE-2018-20796 — glibc / regexp
 
 - **Component:** GNU C Library (`glibc`), POSIX regex / `regexec`
 - **Class of issue:** Resource exhaustion via crafted expression (policy: not a security bug per glibc wiki)
 - **Debian tracker:** Bullseye, Bookworm, **Trixie** (`glibc` e.g. `2.41-12+deb13u2`), sid/forky — listed **vulnerable**; **fixed version (unfixed)**; **unimportant**
 - **Related discussion:** Debian notes link [debbugs.gnu.org #34141](https://debbugs.gnu.org/cgi/bugreport.cgi?bug=34141) and [bug-gnulib thread](https://lists.gnu.org/archive/html/bug-gnulib/2019-01/msg00108.html)
 
 ### Illustrative tracker view
 
 | Release  | Package | High-level Debian posture     |
 |----------|---------|--------------------------------|
 | bullseye | glibc   | vulnerable row / unimportant |
 | bookworm | glibc   | vulnerable row / unimportant |
 | trixie   | glibc   | vulnerable row / unimportant |
 | sid      | glibc   | unfixed / unimportant        |
 
 There is **no separate “trixie security fix”** whose purpose is to satisfy this CVE as a supported remediation path.
 
 ---
 
 ## Why Rebuilding glibc in Containers Is the Wrong Default
 
 - Replacing distro `glibc` is fragile and breaks ABI expectations for the entire image
 - Upstream does not offer this as a **security fix** under their published policy
 - **Do not** feed untrusted regex to libc matchers; that is the operational control that matches vendor intent
 
 ---
 
 ## Audits: Wording vs. “False Positive”
 
 The CVE ID is still attached to real `glibc` packages, so many teams avoid calling it a strict **false positive**. Clear alternatives:
 
 - **Not a security vulnerability per glibc Security Exceptions and Debian (unimportant)**  
 - **Accepted risk / exception** with tracker and wiki citations
 
 **Recommendation:** Document CVE-2018-20796 as **non-actionable** for stock Debian **Trixie** images for security-remediation purposes, unless you have an unusual requirement to compile a private `glibc` (almost never justified for this CVE alone).
 
 ---
 
 ## Summary
 
 - CVE-2018-20796 is a **resource exhaustion / regexp** report; glibc policy: **not a security vulnerability**
 - Debian: **unimportant**, **(unfixed)** — no vendor patch story aligned with scanner “fix” expectations
 - **Trixie** is in the same posture as other current Debian releases in the tracker
 - Prefer **policy exception / not actionable** language over a bare **false positive** unless your glossary defines FP broadly
 
 ---
 
 ## References
 
 - [glibc wiki – Security Exceptions](https://sourceware.org/glibc/wiki/Security%20Exceptions)
 - [Debian Security Tracker – CVE-2018-20796](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2018-20796)
 - [NVD – CVE-2018-20796](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2018-20796)
