+- **Package:** `glibc`
+- **Trixie (example):** `2.41-12+deb13u2` — row still shows **vulnerable**
+- **Fixed version (unstable):** **(unfixed)**
+- **Urgency:** **unimportant**
+- **Notes:** **Not treated as a security issue by upstream** → [Sourceware Bugzilla #22851](https://sourceware.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=22851)
+
+There is **no Debian security update** whose role is to “patch CVE-2019-1010023” the way normal glibc advisories work.
+
+---
+
+## Why scanners still flag stock Debian images
+
+Tools map **installed `glibc`** to CVE metadata. They generally **do not** encode:
+
+- That exploitation hinges on **social engineering / misuse** (`ldd` on malicious ELFs)
+- Upstream’s **non-security** classification
+- Debian’s **unimportant** + **(unfixed)** posture
+
+So compliance dashboards can show a critical-sounding CVE even when **distributors do not plan a CVE-specific fix**.
+
+---
+
+## CVE-2019-1010023 — glibc / `ldd` / loader
+
+- **Component:** `glibc` — `ldd` / dynamic linker (`libld` / `ld.so` interaction)
+- **Attack shape (CVE narrative):** User runs `ldd` on crafted ELF(s) supplied by an attacker
+- **Upstream:** Non-security bug; no real threat (BZ #22851)
+- **Debian:** Bullseye, Bookworm, **Trixie**, sid/forky — **vulnerable** rows; **(unfixed)**; **unimportant**
+
+### Illustrative tracker view
